thread.title: Bell: Kirk Cousins takes big step out of Robert Griffin III's shadow
thread.title_full: Bell: Kirk Cousins takes big step out of Robert Griffin III's shadow

author: azcentral.com
title: Bell: Kirk Cousins takes big step out of Robert Griffin III's shadow
text:
LANDOVER, Md. — It was such a moment of truth for Kirk Cousins — the final minutes at FedEx Field on Sunday were more than tense — that the last person you’d expect to see on the field was ...
Robert Griffin III.
But the first signature drive of Cousins’ NFL career — the Washington quarterback capped his first fourth-quarter comeback victory by nailing a 4-yard strike to Pierre Garcon with 26 seconds left — indeed included an RG3 cameo. It happened with 42 seconds on the clock, when play was interrupted while Jordan Reed lay on the turf, evaluated for a concussion. Griffin, dressed in sweats as the inactive No. 3 quarterback, left the sideline and walked to the spot where trainers were attending to the injured tight end.
After a brief glance at Reed, Griffin didn’t make a bee-line back to the bench. He looked a bit lost, seemingly close to drifting toward the huddle. It had to be a weird feeling for RG3, three years ago the toast of D.C., now reduced to a mere spectator.
Griffin might have been headed in the direction of Cousins, who used the timeout for a sideline confab with coach Jay Gruden. They made eye contact, but Cousins kept moving back to the huddle. Griffin returned to the sideline.
USA TODAY

It was an awkward snapshot from a dramatic 23-20 win over the rival Philadelphia Eagles, overshadowed by Washington’s last-minute heroics and another collapse by Chip Kelly’s 1-3 team.
Did Griffin say anything to Cousins?
“I don’t remember," Cousins said when I asked about the exchange afterward. “I don’t think so.”
It’s plausible that he didn't remember. He was undoubtedly locked in during crunch time. On the next snap, he executed a deft pump-fake, then connected with Garcon on a slant for a 12-yard gain. On the touchdown throw, Cousins threw a sizzling dart into a window so tight that Garcon didn’t even know he had crossed the goal line because he was knocked every which way by three defenders in his vicinity.
Cousins took a big step toward proving that he can handle his new role. The skepticism about him has included a knack for untimely turnovers, and a sense that he does not handle adversity well. In other words, everything has to be perfect.
Well, that certainly wasn’t the case Sunday, when Washington blew a 13-point lead. In the first half, the team couldn’t finish two drives and settled for short field goals. And the first touchdown? Cousins fumbled the snap at the 1-yard line but recovered the ball and pushed into the end zone.
Yet on the 15-play, 90-yard, game-winning drive, it was apparent that Cousins and Gruden grew. Washington (2-2) started the previous drive from its 10-yard line, too, but went three-and-out when Cousins, under heavy pressure, threw a pass from his end zone at Alfred Morris’ feet. The next pass was dropped before a completion that went for no gain.
Granted another chance, Gruden decided to run the ball out of the danger zone. Morris ripped off 16- and 6-yard runs to jump-start the march. Then Gruden put the game entirely on the arm of his young quarterback. It helped that Garcon, who suffered a knee sprain, returned — emblematic of all the talk about resiliency in the post-game interviews.
But it started with Cousins, who didn’t commit a turnover and in crunch time did what the big-time quarterbacks are prone to do. He led the way.
“That final drive, I wasn’t capable of doing that when I came into the league as a rookie,” said Cousins, the fourth-round pick from the same draft class that produced Griffin in 2012. “It takes time, it takes failures, it takes learning from experiences.
“I guess it would be three-plus seasons worth of work got me to a point where I was able to make the necessary plays on that drive. So you know it’s a process.”
That sounds like a man finding a comfort zone.
Although Cousins maintains Griffin has been supportive during the week and on game days, the presence of such a high-profile figure is worth watching. If Cousins falters, a quarterback controversy can easily ignite in a city that loves debate.
But Cousins hardly seems to be looking over his shoulder.
“I just block out the noise,” he told me as he left the stadium.
“I’m going to take it one day at a time. If I do that, I feel like the results will take care of themselves.”
***
Follow NFL columnist Jarrett Bell on Twitter @JarrettBell
